  "body": "### Description\r\nIn this feature, only validators with a valid certificate can propose valid blocks. Upon receiving a block proposal, all validators must validate if the proposal contains a valid certificate.\r\n\r\nEvery block in the blockchain will keep the authorization information as part of the block header (in the extra data).\r\n\r\nThe authorization information (also known as \"stamp\") is created as a CMS message and added to the extraData field in the block header. We append the CMS message as the last element in the extraData' RLP list.\r\n\r\n### Acceptance Criteria\r\n* Only blocks with a CMS message are valid.\r\n* Validators must verify the CMS message upon receiving a proposal before committing to the block.\r\n* When proposing a block, the validator must include its authorizing certificate, any intermediate certificate required to validate the chain, and a signature of the block to ensure this CMS message is unique to that block.\r\n\r\n### Other Information\r\n* Non-validator nodes won't perform the certificate validation when synchronising blocks. They will only check if the \"stamp\" is present in the block header. The actual verification is performed by validators during the proposal round. Because the CMS message is part of the block hash calculation, any tampering with the CMS message will be detected.\r\n* Draft work can be found on this branch (https://github.com/lucassaldanha/besu/tree/pki-qbft-behaviour)",
